body:
Thanks for taking the time to report this.

Can you please attach an example that shows the issue or missing feature? 
According to Section 7.6 in IEEE 1800-2023, assigning an array in big-endian ordering to an array declared in little endian ordering should assign elements left-to-right:
>Assignment shall be done by assigning each element of the source array to the corresponding element of the
>target array. Correspondence between elements is determined by the left-to-right order of elements in each
>array. For example, if array A is declared as int A[7:0] and array B is declared as int B[1:8], the
>assignment A = B; will assign element B[1] to element A[7], and so on

However, if the type returned by a function is a big-endian array and the output of the function is assigned to a little-endian array parameter, this does not hold - see the following example.

```systemverilog
module t(/* AUTOARG */);
    typedef logic [31:0] be_unpacked_arr_t [8];
    typedef logic [31:0] le_unpacked_arr_t [7:0];
    function automatic be_unpacked_arr_t foo ();
        be_unpacked_arr_t arr;
        for (int i = 0; i < 8; i++) begin
            arr[i] = i;
        end
        return arr;
    endfunction

    localparam le_unpacked_arr_t LE_PARAM = foo();

    initial begin
        for (int i = 0; i < 8; i++) begin
            if (LE_PARAM[i] != 8 - 1 - i) $stop;
        end
        $write("*-* All Finished *-*\n");
        $finish;
    end
endmodule
```
What 'verilator' command line do we use to run your example?
Using the `test_regress` driver, or `verilator --binary -j 0 t/t.v`

What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?  Did you try it with other simulators?
Verilator 5.040 2025-08-30 rev v5.040-50-g0a9d9db5a. Also tried with Verilator 5.041 devel rev v5.040-261-g832f41f0f, same result. 

This test works with both Questa and XSim.

What OS and distribution are you using?
Fedora 29

